name: I Couldn't Take My Eyes off You
The Lambton Worm
comments: Roud #2337 The Legend of the Lambton Worm, which dates back to the 18th century, being printed in 1785 by William Hutchinson in his book 'The history and antiquities of the County Palatine of Durham’, but is rooted in local oral traditions dating back to the 14th century. In fokelore a worm is often used to describe snakes, serpents and dragons. The Lambton Worm recounts the story of young Lambton, the heir to the Lambton Estate, who, instead of attending church, caught a peculiar eel-like creature with a dragon's head while fishing in the River Wear. Unaware of the creature's potential, he discarded it down a well, ultimately unleashing a monstrous and ravenous worm upon the region. After many years and a transformation, Lambton returns from a crusade, seeking a way to vanquish the beast. With the guidance of a wise woman, he confronts the worm in the River Wear, donning armor studded with razors. The battle ends with the worm's demise, relieving the terrified locals. However, Lambton's omission to fulfill the witch's advice brings a curse upon his family for nine generations, ensuring they don't die peacefully in their beds. The song was first performed as part of a pantomime performed at The Tyne Theatre & Opera House in 1867.

name: Pretty Polly Perkins of Paddington Green
comments: Roud No. 430 The music to this tune, like others by Clifton , could be based upon older songs 'Nightingales Sing' , also known as 'The Bold Grenadier' Chorus: She was as beautiful as a butterfly and proud as a Queen Was pretty little Polly Perkins of Paddington Green The song tells the story of a heartbroken milkman who falls in love with a beautiful young servant maid named Polly Perkins, who works in a gentleman's house near Paddington Green. The milkman admires Polly's beauty and longs for her affection but is ultimately rejected when he proposes marriage. Polly demands a wealthier and more impressive suitor, leading the milkman to leave in sadness. In the end, Polly marries a less prestigious man, a bow-legged conductor of a tuppenny bus. The song reflects the milkman's unrequited love and Polly's materialistic expectations.

name: Cushie Butterfield
comments: Roud No. 3504 A Geordie folk song, parodies the song 'Pretty Polly Perkins of Paddington Green' by Harry Clifton. Despite being published before Polly, the song was written after the original. Chorus: She's a big lass an' a bonnie lass an' she likes hor beor An' they caall hor Cushie Butterfield and Aa wish she was heor The song is about a lovesick keelman (boatman) who is deeply in love with a young woman named Cushie Butterfield from Gateshead, the exact opposite to Polly in Clifton's song. A big, beer-loving woman, described unpleasantly as a 'bag full of sawdust tied round with a string'. She sells yellow clay, used to polish the doorsteps of well-to-do houses. The keelman admires Cushie despite her appearance and working-class job. Proposing, he is initially laughed off by Cushie, but later she bursts into tears.
